Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 400 degrees. Cut @sweet potatoes{2} into ½-inch cubes. Strip @thyme{¼%bunch}(leaves stripped from stems, stems discarded) leaves from stems; discard stems. Finely chop leaves.

Toss sweet potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with half the thyme, a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tbsp}, and a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Roast in oven until tender and crisped, about ~{25%minutes} total (we'll check on them after ~{10%minutes}).

Once sweet potatoes have roasted ~{10%minutes}, give them a toss and push toward one side of sheet. Add @green beans{6} to same sheet and toss with a large drizzle of olive oil. Season with salt and pepper. Return to oven and roast until green beans are tender and potatoes are done, about ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a large drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season @ranch-cut steaks{2} all over with salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-6%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and let rest ~{5%minutes}.

Add @beef demi-glace{1%pack}, @water{¼%cup}, and remaining thyme to same pan over medium-high heat and stir, scraping up any browned bits from bottom. Let simmer until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Remove from heat and add @butter{1%tbsp}, stirring or swirling pan to melt. Season with salt and pepper.

Sprinkle @sliced almonds{1%tbsp} over green beans and sweet potatoes on baking sheet. Thinly slice steak against the grain. Divide green beans, sweet potatoes, and steak between plates. Drizzle with pan sauce and serve.

> Even plain Janes like to get dressed up and have a night on the town every now and then, and this recipe was designed in that spirit. Ooh la la indeed.